<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1322,427,774]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Newly recorded on Prince Edward Island: scattered distribution in the Maritime Provinces (
<figureCitation box="[395,465,548,574]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[264,368,1191,1215]" captionTargetBox="[561,1026,830,1167]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[561,1027,830,1167]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of Pedilus lugubris in the Maritime Provinces of Canada." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172999/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">
Fig. 
<number box="[449,465,548,574]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[520,608,548,574]" name="Canada" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Canada</collectingCountry>
recorded from Ontario east to Nova 
<collectingCountry box="[1036,1109,548,574]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">Scotia</collectingCountry>
(Bousquet 
<number box="[1244,1306,548,574]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1991.0">1991</number>
); in the 
<collectingCountry box="[350,513,588,614]" name="United States of America" pageId="6" pageNumber="43">United States</collectingCountry>
recorded from Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont, Massachusetts (
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler" box="[272,455,628,654]" pageId="6" pageNumber="49" refString="Chandler, D. S. (2001) University of New Hampshire Insect and Arachnid Collections. Available from http: // insectcoll. unh. edu / [cited 19 March 2006]." type="journal article" year="2001">
Chandler 
<number box="[393,455,628,654]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and New York west to Illinois (
<bibRefCitation author="Downie" box="[875,1167,628,654]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" refString="Downie, N. M. &amp; Arnett, R. H., Jr. (1996) The beetles of northeastern North America. Sandhill Crane Press, Gainesville, Florida. 1721 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Downie &amp; Arnett 
<number box="[1104,1167,628,654]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae are associated with cool, moist sub­cortical conditions between loosened bark and decaying wood of deciduous and coniferous trees; adults are common on shrubs and flowers (
<bibRefCitation author="Young" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" refString="Young, D. A. (2002) Pyrochroidae Latreille 1807. In: Arnett, R. H., Jr., Thomas, M. C., Skelley, P. E. &amp; Frank, J. H. (Eds.). American Beetles, Volume 2: Polyphaga: Scarabaeoidea through Curculionoidea. CRC Press, Boca Raton, USA. pp. 540 - 543." type="journal article" year="2002">
Young 
<number box="[264,328,748,774]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
